  "learnings_before": "- Both valproate and carbamazepine are guideline‑consistent first‑line options for focal seizures in children ≤ 2 years; selection is guided by drug availability, tolerability, and the need for laboratory monitoring.\n- Aromatic AEDs (carbamazepine, lamotrigine, phenytoin) are acceptable for focal epilepsy but must be avoided in any child with a documented drug‑induced rash or hypersensitivity.\n- Before any change of therapy, clinicians must obtain baseline safety labs (ALT/AST < 2 × ULN, platelet count > 150 × 10⁹/L, ammonia within normal limits) and, when feasible, a serum level of the current AED.\n- Dose optimisation is performed first: if the current dose is < 20 mg/kg/day for valproate or < 15 mg/kg/day for carbamazepine and seizure control is suboptimal, the dose should be titrated upward in 25‑50 mg increments every 1–2 weeks before considering drug substitution or adjuncts.\n- Exaggerated startles, feeding difficulty, or increased tone in children with cerebral palsy are not automatically attributed to drug toxicity; they require confirmation (e.g., seizure diary or video‑EEG) before altering the regimen.\n- The decision hierarchy is: (1) confirm seizure‑free status (≥ 6 months) and adherence ≥ 80 %; (2) verify normal safety labs; (3) maintain the current regimen unchanged; (4) if either seizure control or labs are inadequate, proceed to dose optimisation; (5) if optimisation fails, consider switching to valproate (after normal LFTs) or adding levetiracetam as an adjunct.\n- Valproate is stocked in >90 % of district pharmacies at ≈ $0.08 per 100 mg; carbamazepine is similarly stocked at ≈ $0.05 per 100 mg; levetiracetam is 2–3 × more expensive and often unavailable, so it is reserved for documented valproate intolerance or failure.\n- Phenobarbital is reserved for refractory cases or when both valproate and levetiracetam are unavailable; it may be used in spastic cerebral palsy only with close monitoring for sedation, otherwise it is avoided.\n- Initiation of valproate requires baseline liver function tests and ammonia; if ALT/AST > 2 × ULN or ammonia is elevated, valproate should be deferred and an alternative AED chosen.\n- When a child is seizure‑free on a stable valproate dose within the therapeutic window (20–30 mg/kg/day) and safety labs are normal, the protocol mandates continuation of the exact current dose without escalation or adjunct addition.",
  "candidate_learnings": "- Carbamazepine is the preferred first‑line agent for focal seizures in children ≤ 2 years; valproate is reserved for generalized seizures or when carbamazepine is contraindicated.\n- A therapeutic trial requires a minimum dose of ≥ 15 mg/kg/day for carbamazepine or ≥ 20 mg/kg/day for valproate for at least 2 weeks before any change is considered.\n- Refractory epilepsy is defined as breakthrough seizures after a therapeutic trial at the target dose and duration.\n- Valproate is avoided in children with hepatic dysfunction, elevated ammonia, or thrombocytopenia unless recent labs are within normal limits; in cerebral palsy patients it is used only after safety confirmation.\n- Phenobarbital is the cheapest AED and is employed as an adjunct in refractory cases or when both carbamazepine and levetiracetam are unavailable.\n- Levetiracetam is the first‑line adjunct for focal epilepsy after carbamazepine optimisation, but its use is limited by higher cost and lower availability in district pharmacies.\n- Lamotrigine is not recommended for myoclonic or generalized seizures, especially when combined with valproate, due to interaction‑induced rash risk and the need for very slow titration.\n- Common low‑resource failure modes (missed doses, improper storage, concurrent herbal remedies) must be screened before adjusting medication.\n- Baseline safety labs (ALT/AST, CBC, ammonia) are required before initiating or switching to valproate; repeat LFTs at 2 weeks and then every 3 months, with carbamazepine levels checked if feasible.\n- Adherence ≥ 80 % must be confirmed prior to dose escalation or drug substitution.\n- Behavioral changes such as hyperactivity are more often related to comorbid ADHD than to valproate toxicity unless laboratory abnormalities are present.\n- In Ugandan district pharmacies carbamazepine (~$0.05/100 mg) and valproate (~$0.08/100 mg) are stocked in > 90 % of facilities; levetiracetam (~$0.24/100 mg) in ~30 %; phenobarbital (~$0.03/100 mg) in ~78 %.\n- The “minimum effective therapy” principle directs clinicians to maintain the simplest regimen that achieves seizure control, adding adjuncts only after maximal tolerated monotherapy doses have failed.\n- Future teratogenic risk counseling is necessary for adolescent females on valproate; it does not influence current therapy for pre‑pubertal boys.\n- Children with cerebral palsy often tolerate phenobarbital’s sedative effects; monitoring for excessive tone or respiratory depression is advised.",
